<p><b>Geoffrey Chaucer</b> (<span class="nowrap"><small>pron.:</small> <span title="Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)" class="IPA"><a href="Help_IPA_for_English" title="Help:IPA for English">/</a></span><span class="IPA"><a href="Help_IPA_for_English#Key" title="Help:IPA for English"><span title="/ˈ/ primary stress follows" style="border-bottom:1px dotted">ˈ</span></a></span><span class="IPA"><a href="Help_IPA_for_English#Key" title="Help:IPA for English"><span title="/tʃ/ 'ch' in 'china'" style="border-bottom:1px dotted">tʃ</span></a></span><span class="IPA"><a href="Help_IPA_for_English#Key" title="Help:IPA for English"><span title="/ɔː/ 'au' in 'fraud'" style="border-bottom:1px dotted">ɔː</span></a></span><span class="IPA"><a href="Help_IPA_for_English#Key" title="Help:IPA for English"><span title="'s' in 'sigh'" style="border-bottom:1px dotted">s</span></a></span><span class="IPA"><a href="Help_IPA_for_English#Key" title="Help:IPA for English"><span title="/ər/ 'er' in 'finger'" style="border-bottom:1px dotted">ər</span></a></span><span title="Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)" class="IPA"><a href="Help_IPA_for_English" title="Help:IPA for English">/</a></span></span>; c. 1343 – 25 October 1400), known as the Father of <a href="English_literature" title="English literature">English literature</a>, is widely considered the greatest English poet of the <a href="Middle_Ages" title="Middle Ages">Middle Ages</a> and was the first poet to have been buried in <a href="Poet's_Corner" title="Poet's Corner" class="mw-redirect">Poet's Corner</a> of <a href="Westminster_Abbey" title="Westminster Abbey">Westminster Abbey</a>. While he achieved fame during his lifetime as an author, philosopher, <a href="Alchemist" title="Alchemist" class="mw-redirect">alchemist</a> and <a href="Astronomer" title="Astronomer">astronomer</a>, composing a scientific treatise on the <a href="Astrolabe" title="Astrolabe">astrolabe</a> for his ten year-old son Lewis, Chaucer also maintained an active career in the civil service as a bureaucrat, <a href="Noble_court" title="Noble court" class="mw-redirect">courtier</a> and diplomat. Among his many works, which include <i><a href="The_Book_of_the_Duchess" title="The Book of the Duchess">The Book of the Duchess</a></i>, the <i><a href="House_of_Fame" title="House of Fame" class="mw-redirect">House of Fame</a></i>, the <i><a href="Legend_of_Good_Women" title="Legend of Good Women" class="mw-redirect">Legend of Good Women</a></i> and <i><a href="Troilus_and_Criseyde" title="Troilus and Criseyde">Troilus and Criseyde</a></i>, he is best known today for <i><a href="The_Canterbury_Tales" title="The Canterbury Tales">The Canterbury Tales</a></i>. Chaucer is a crucial figure in developing the legitimacy of the <a href="Vernacular" title="Vernacular">vernacular</a>, <a href="Middle_English" title="Middle English">Middle English</a>, at a time when the dominant literary languages in England were French and Latin.</p>
